Here's the registration pattern:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient factory — manages socket lifetime for you
        builder.Services.AddHttpClient<IDataService, DataService>(client =>
        {
            client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com/");
        });

        // ViewModels — transient so each navigation gets fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so they bind to their own ViewModel instance
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `DataService` | **Singleton** (via `AddHttpClient`) | Stateless API wrapper — one instance is enough. `AddHttpClient` manages `HttpClient` pooling/socket reuse so you avoid socket exhaustion. |
| `MainViewModel` / `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation should get a clean VM with fresh state. Singleton VMs would leak stale data between navigations. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Each page gets its own ViewModel injected via constructor. Matches the transient VM lifetime so they stay paired. |

**Key rule of thumb:** services that hold no per-request state → singleton. UI components (pages/VMs) that hold screen-specific state → transient. Avoid scoped in MAUI — there's no built-in scope-per-navigation.
